# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: energy-quality
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] In ecology, **abiotic components** or **abiotic factors** are non-living chemical and physical parts of the environment that affect living organisms and the functioning of ecosystems.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors and the phenomena associated with them underpin biology as a whole.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] They affect a wide range of species, across all forms of environmental conditions, such as marine or terrestrial animals.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Humans can make or change abiotic factors in a species' environment.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] For instance, fertilizers can affect a snail's habitat, or the greenhouse gases which humans utilize can change marine pH levels.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Abiotic components include physical conditions and non-living resources that affect living organisms in terms of growth, maintenance, and reproduction.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Resources are distinguished as substances or objects in the environment required by one organism and consumed or otherwise made unavailable for use by other organisms.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Component degradation of a substance occurs by chemical or physical processes, e.g. hydrolysis.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] All non-living components of an ecosystem, such as atmospheric conditions and water resources, are called abiotic components.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] In biology, abiotic factors can include water, light, radiation, temperature, humidity, atmosphere, acidity, salinity, precipitation, altitude, minerals, tides, rain, dissolved oxygen nutrients, and soil.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] The macroscopic climate often influences each of the above.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Pressure and sound waves may also be considered in the context of marine or sub-terrestrial environments.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors in ocean environments also include aerial exposure, substrate, water clarity, solar energy and tides.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Consider the differences in the mechanics of C3, C4, and CAM plants in regulating the influx of carbon dioxide to the Calvin-Benson Cycle in relation to their abiotic stressors.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] C3 plants have no mechanisms to manage photorespiration, whereas C4 and CAM plants utilize a separate PEP carboxylase enzyme to prevent photorespiration, thus increasing the yield of photosynthesis processes in certain high energy environments.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Many Archea require very high temperatures, pressures, or unusual concentrations of chemical substances such as sulfur; this is due to their specialization into extreme conditions.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] In addition, fungi have also evolved to survive at the temperature, the humidity, and stability of their environment.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] For example, there is a significant difference in access to both water and humidity between temperate rain forests and deserts.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] This difference in water availability causes a diversity in the organisms that survive in these areas.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] These differences in abiotic components alter the species present by creating boundaries of what species can survive within the environment and influencing competition between two species.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-component] Abiotic factors such as salinity can give one species a competitive advantage over another, creating pressures that lead to speciation and alteration of a species to and from generalist and specialist competitors.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is essentially unavoidable.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress affects animals, but plants are especially dependent, if not solely dependent, on environmental factors, so it is particularly constraining.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress is the most harmful factor concerning the growth and productivity of crops worldwide.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Research has also shown that abiotic stressors are at their most harmful when they occur together, in combinations of abiotic stress factors.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The most common of the stressors are the easiest for people to identify, but there are many other, less recognizable abiotic stress factors which affect environments constantly.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Lesser-known stressors generally occur on a smaller scale.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] They include: poor edaphic conditions like rock content and pH levels, high radiation, compaction, contamination, and other, highly specific conditions like rapid rehydration during seed germination.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress, as a natural part of every ecosystem, will affect organisms in a variety of ways.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Although these effects may be either beneficial or detrimental, the location of the area is crucial in determining the extent of the impact that abiotic stress will have.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The higher the latitude of the area affected, the greater the impact of abiotic stress will be on that area.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] So, a taiga or boreal forest is at the mercy of whatever abiotic stress factors may come along, while tropical zones are much less susceptible to such stressors.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] While abiotic stress may have negative impacts on individual organisms, there are cases where abiotic stress plays an important role in maintaining a healthy ecosystem.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Important ecosystem mechanisms and improved overall stress tolerance may rely on occasional low levels of abiotic stress.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] One example of a situation where abiotic stress plays a constructive role in an ecosystem is in natural wildfires.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Smaller fires are useful in reducing the overall fuel load of an area of forest or prairie.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] By clearing out dead brush and other organic matter, the risk of catastrophic and widespread fire decreases, and the residual ash of smaller fires helps add nutrients back into the soil.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The observed benefits of these smaller and more controlled fires on land usability and species populations have led to the use of prescribed burning by humans for centuries.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Varying perspectives on the benefits and risks of fire to ecosystems have influenced official policy through history.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Forest Service, initially focused on fire control, changed its policy to one of fire management in 1974, recognizing these fires as a natural part of an ecosystem.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] There is also evidence that a diverse fire history between patches of land within an area has been shown to benefit transitional landscapes between savanna and forest.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Even though it is healthy for an ecosystem, a wildfire can still be considered an abiotic stressor, because it puts stress on individual organisms within the area.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] On the larger scale, though, natural wildfires are positive manifestations of abiotic stress.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] What also needs to be taken into account when looking for benefits of abiotic stress, is that one phenomenon may not affect an entire ecosystem in the same way.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] While a flood will kill most plants living low on the ground in a certain area, if there is rice there, it will thrive in the wet conditions.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Another example of this is in phytoplankton and zooplankton.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The same types of conditions are usually considered stressful for these two types of organisms.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] They act very similarly when exposed to ultraviolet light and most toxins, but at elevated temperatures the phytoplankton reacts negatively, while the thermophilic zooplankton reacts positively to the increase in temperature.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The two may be living in the same environment, but an increase in temperature of the area would prove stressful only for one of the organisms.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Lastly, abiotic stress has enabled species to grow, develop, and evolve, through the process of natural selection.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Heritable traits that improve an organism's resiliency under stressed conditions increase the likelihood that the organism will survive and reproduce, enabling it to pass these traits to the next generation.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Both plants and animals have evolved mechanisms allowing them to survive extremes.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] One of the detriments concerning abiotic stress involves farming.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] It has been claimed by one study that abiotic stress causes the most crop loss of any other factor and that most major crops are reduced in their yield by more than 50% from their potential yield.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Because abiotic stress is widely considered a detrimental effect, the research on this branch of the issue is extensive.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] For more information on the harmful effects of abiotic stress, see the sections below on plants and animals.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] A plant's first line of defense against abiotic stress is in its roots.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] If the soil holding the plant is healthy and biologically diverse, the plant will have a higher chance of surviving stressful conditions.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The plant responses to stress are dependent on the tissue or organ affected by the stress.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] For example, transcriptional responses to stress are tissue or cell specific in roots and are quite different depending on the stress involved.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] One of the primary responses to abiotic stress such as high salinity is the disruption of the Na+/K+ ratio in the cytoplasm of the plant cell.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] High concentrations of Na+, for example, can decrease the capacity for the plant to take up water and also alter enzyme and transporter functions.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Evolved adaptations to efficiently restore cellular ion homeostasis have led to a wide variety of stress tolerant plants.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Facilitation, or the positive interactions between different species of plants, is an intricate web of association in a natural environment.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] In areas of high stress, the level of facilitation is especially high as well.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] This could possibly be because the plants need a stronger network to survive in a harsher environment, so their interactions between species, such as cross-pollination or mutualistic actions, become more common to cope with the severity of their habitat.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Plants also adapt very differently from one another, even from a plant living in the same area.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] When a group of different plant species was prompted by a variety of different stress signals, such as drought or cold, each plant responded uniquely.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Hardly any of the responses were similar, even though the plants had become accustomed to exactly the same home environment.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Serpentine soils (media with low concentrations of nutrients and high concentrations of heavy metals) can be a source of abiotic stress.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Initially, the absorption of toxic metal ions is limited by cell membrane exclusion.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Ions that are absorbed into tissues are sequestered in cell vacuoles.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] This sequestration mechanism is facilitated by proteins on the vacuole membrane.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] An example of plants that adapt to serpentine soil are Metallophytes, or hyperaccumulators, as they are known for their ability to absorbed heavy metals using the root-to-shoot translocation (which it will absorb into shoots rather than the plant itself).
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] They're also extinguished for their ability to absorb toxic substances from heavy metals.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Chemical priming has been proposed to increase tolerance to abiotic stresses in crop plants.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] In this method, which is analogous to vaccination, stress-inducing chemical agents are introduced to the plant in brief doses so that the plant begins preparing defense mechanisms.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Thus, when the abiotic stress occurs, the plant has already prepared defense mechanisms that can be activated faster and increase tolerance.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Abiotic stress mostly affects plants used in agriculture.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Some examples of adverse conditions (which may be caused by climate change) are high or low temperatures, drought, salinity, and toxins.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Elevated global temperatures present a severe bottleneck for crop yields, as heat stress alters membrane fluidity, accelerates destructive transpiration rates, and heavily impairs a plant's overall Water Use Efficiency (WUE).
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] When crops encounter extreme thermal environments during early reproductive or vegetative stages, cellular homeostasis is broken down, causing grain yield reduction and premature leaf senescence.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] To mitigate down-stream damage from overlapping thermal and drought shocks, advanced ex-ante strategies such as physical seed priming or chemical priming agents are applied.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] These priming interventions activate early molecular, enzymatic, and hormonal pre-defense responses within the seed tissue, enabling the plant to maintain higher functional stability and lower oxidative injury when heat stress occurs later in the field environment.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Flooding acts as a compound environmental stressor that is broadly categorized into waterlogging (where only the root system is inundated) and complete submergence (where the entire plant is covered by water).
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The primary hazard of flooding is gas diffusion restriction, which triggers oxygen starvation (hypoxia or anoxia) in the rhizosphere and alters essential plant hormone signaling networks, such as the regulation between Sub1A and non-Sub1A genotypes in rice.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] To cope with complete submergence, tolerant plants rely on distinct physiological survival strategies.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Furthermore, monitoring maximum quantum yield performance reveals that preserving photosynthetic efficiency during transient flooding stress is paramount to driving rapid physiological recovery once the water recedes.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Soil acidity acts as a sweeping abiotic stress factor on global arable lands, primarily because low pH environments trigger dangerous chemical toxicities dominated by soluble aluminum (Al3+ )and iron, which structurally damage root anatomy and limit basic development.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] High acidity also locks up vital macronutrients, causing severe phosphorus starvation stress that forces plants to aggressively modify their lateral root structures to maximize surface area absorption.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] To remediate heavy-metal-polluted and highly acidic substrates, bioremediation utilizes hyperaccumulator plant traits (metallophytes).
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] These specialized plants successfully survive the toxicity of acidic media by relying on a highly developed root-to-shoot translocation system, which efficiently absorbs and transports toxic ions away from fragile root tissues and sequesters them safely inside the upper shoot vacuoles.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Soil salinization, the accumulation of water-soluble salts to levels that negatively impact plant production, is a global phenomenon affecting approximately 831 million hectares of land.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] More specifically, the phenomenon threatens 19.5% of the world's irrigated agricultural land and 2.1% of the world's non-irrigated (dry-land) agricultural lands.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] High soil salinity content can be harmful to plants because water-soluble salts can alter osmotic potential gradients and consequently inhibit many cellular functions.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Over generations, many plants have mutated and built different mechanisms to counter salinity effects.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] A good combatant of salinity in plants is the hormone ethylene.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Ethylene is known for regulating plant growth and development and dealing with stress conditions.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Many central membrane proteins in plants, such as ETO2, ERS1 and EIN2, are used for ethylene signaling in many plant growth processes.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Mutations in these proteins can lead to heightened salt sensitivity and can limit plant growth.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The effects of salinity has been studied on *Arabidopsis* plants that have mutated ERS1, ERS2, ETR1, ETR2 and EIN4 proteins.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] These proteins are used for ethylene signaling against certain stress conditions, such as salt and the ethylene precursor ACC is used to suppress any sensitivity to the salt stress.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus (P) is an essential macronutrient required for plant growth and development, but it is present only in limited quantities in most of the world's soil.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Plants use P mainly in the form of soluble inorganic phosphates (PO4−−−) but are subject to abiotic stress when there is not enough soluble PO4−−− in the soil.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Phosphorus forms insoluble complexes with Ca and Mg in alkaline soils and with Al and Fe in acidic soils that make the phosphorus unavailable for plant roots.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] It has been shown that PHR1, a MYB-related transcription factor, is a master regulator of P-starvation response in plants.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Drought stress, defined as naturally occurring water deficit, is a main cause of crop losses in agriculture.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] This is because water is essential for many fundamental processes in plant growth.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] It has become especially important in recent years to find a way to combat drought stress.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] A decrease in precipitation and consequent increase in drought are extremely likely in the future due to an increase in global warming.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Plants have come up with many mechanisms and adaptations to try and deal with drought stress.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] One of the leading ways that plants combat drought stress is by closing their stomata.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] A key hormone regulating stomatal opening and closing is abscisic acid (ABA).
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Synthesis of ABA causes the ABA to bind to receptors.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] This binding then affects the opening of ion channels, thereby decreasing turgor pressure in the stomata and causing them to close.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Recent studies by Gonzalez-Villagra, et al., have shown how ABA levels increased in drought-stressed plants (2018).
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] They showed that when plants were placed in a stressful situation, they produced more ABA to try to conserve any water they had in their leaves.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Another extremely important factor in dealing with drought stress and regulating the uptake and export of water is aquaporins (AQPs).
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] AQPs are integral membrane proteins that make up channels.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] These channels' main job is the transport of water and other essential solutes.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] AQPs are both transcriptionally and post-transcriptionally regulated by many different factors such as ABA, GA3, pH and Ca2+; and the specific levels of AQPs in certain parts of the plant, such as roots or leaves, helps to draw as much water into the plant as possible.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] By understanding the mechanisms of both AQPs and the hormone ABA, scientists will be better able to produce drought-resistant plants in the future.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] A study by Tombesi et al., found that plants which had previously been exposed to drought were able to minimize water loss and decrease water use.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] They found that plants which were exposed to drought conditions actually changed the way they regulated their stomata and what they called "hydraulic safety margin" so as to decrease the vulnerability of the plant.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] By changing the regulation of stomata and subsequently the transpiration, plants were able to function better when less water was available.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] For animals, the most stressful of all the abiotic stressors is heat.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] This is because many species are unable to regulate their internal body temperature.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Even in the species that are able to regulate their own temperature, it is not always a completely accurate system.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Temperature determines metabolic rates, heart rates, and other very important factors within the bodies of animals, so an extreme temperature change can easily distress the animal's body.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Animals can respond to extreme heat, for example, through natural heat acclimation or by burrowing into the ground to find a cooler space.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] It is also possible to see in animals that a high genetic diversity is beneficial in providing resiliency against harsh abiotic stressors.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] This acts as a sort of stock room when a species is plagued by the perils of natural selection.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] A variety of galling insects are among the most specialized and diverse herbivores on the planet, and their extensive protections against abiotic stress factors have helped the insect in gaining that position of honor.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Biodiversity is determined by many things, and one of them is abiotic stress.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] If an environment is highly stressful, biodiversity tends to be low.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] If abiotic stress does not have a strong presence in an area, the biodiversity will be much higher.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] This idea leads into the understanding of how abiotic stress and endangered species are related.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] It has been observed through a variety of environments that as the level of abiotic stress increases, the number of species decreases.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] This means that species are more likely to become population threatened, endangered, and even extinct, when and where abiotic stress is especially harsh.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Data suggests that anthropogenic activity has increased the global temperature, and likely increased the odds of extreme climate events such as drought, fire conditions and flooding.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] Threats to organisms and ecosystem biodiversity due to increased abiotic stress are one major impact of this change.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] The effects of climate change on biomes vary due to the location, patterns of precipitation, and the organisms which inhabit them.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] On the species level, the increased abiotic stress due to climate change can lead to adaptations which increase a species' reproductive success under these conditions.
[src:energy-quality/abiotic-stress] However, such highly specialized adaptations may leave species vulnerable to other stresses.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] In ecology, **local abundance** is the relative representation of a species in a particular ecosystem.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] It is usually measured as the number of individuals found per sample.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] The ratio of abundance of one species to one or multiple other species living in an ecosystem is referred to as relative species abundances.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Both indicators are relevant for computing biodiversity.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] A variety of sampling methods are used to measure abundance.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] For larger animals, these may include spotlight counts, track counts and roadkill counts, as well as presence at monitoring stations.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] In many plant communities the abundances of plant species are measured by plant cover, i.e. the relative area covered by different plant species in a small plot.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Abundance is in simplest terms usually measured by identifying and counting every individual of every species in a given sector.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] It is common for the distribution of species to be skewed so that a few species take up the bulk of individuals collected.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Relative species abundance is calculated by dividing the number of species from one group by the total number of species from all groups.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] These measures are all a part of community ecology.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Understanding patterns within a community is easy when the community has a relatively low number of species.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] However most communities do not have a low number of species.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Measuring species abundance allows for understanding of how species are distributed within an ecosystem.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] For example, salt water marshes have an influx of sea water, causing only a few species which are adapted to be able to survive in both salt and fresh water to be abundant.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Inversely in land locked wetlands, the species abundance is more evenly distributed among the species who live within the wetland.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] In most ecosystems in which abundance has been calculated, most often only a small number of species are abundant, while a large number are pretty rare.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] These abundant species are often generalists, with many rare species being specialists.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] High density of a species in multiple localities will usually lead to it being relatively abundant over all in an ecosystem.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Therefore, high local abundance can be directly linked to high regional distribution.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Species with high abundance are likely to have more offspring, and these offspring in turn are more likely to colonize a new sector of the ecosystem than a species which is less abundant.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Thus begins a positive feedback loop leading to a species distribution in which a few "core species" are wide spread, and the other species are restricted and scarce known as satellite species.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Species abundance distribution (SAD) is one of the main uses of this measurement.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] SAD is a measurement of how common, or rare species are within an ecosystem.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] This allows researchers to assess how different species are distributed throughout an ecosystem.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] SAD is one of the most basic measurements in ecology and is used very often, therefore many different methods of measurement and analysis have developed.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] There are several methods for measuring abundance.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] An example of this is Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] These are measurement methods which involve estimation based on viewing a specific area of a designated size.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] The two Semi-Quantitive Abundance ratings used are known as the D.A.F.O.R, and the A.C.F.O.R.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] These methods are useful for getting a rough estimate of the species abundance in a designated area (quadrant), but they are not exact or objective measurements.
[src:energy-quality/abundance-ecology] Therefore, if another method of measuring abundance is available, it should be used, as this will lead to more useful and quantifiable data.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The **Allee effect** is a phenomenon in biology characterized by a correlation between population size or density and the mean individual fitness (often measured as *per capita* population growth rate) of a population or species.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Although the concept of Allee effect had no title at the time, it was first described in the 1930s by its namesake, Warder Clyde Allee.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Through experimental studies, Allee was able to demonstrate that goldfish have a greater survival rate when there are more individuals in the tank.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This led him to conclude that aggregation can improve the survival rate of individuals, and that cooperation may be crucial in the overall evolution of social structure.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The term "Allee principle" was introduced in the 1950s, a time when the field of ecology was heavily focused on the role of competition among and within species.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The classical view of population dynamics stated that due to competition for resources, a population will experience a reduced overall growth rate at higher density and increased growth rate at lower density.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] In other words, individuals in a population would be better off when there are fewer individuals around, due to a limited amount of resources (see logistic growth).
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] However, the concept of the Allee effect introduced the idea that the reverse holds true when the population density is low.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Individuals within a species often require the assistance of another individual for more than simple reproductive reasons in order to persist.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The most obvious example of this is observed in animals that hunt for prey or defend against predators as a group.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The generally accepted definition of Allee effect is positive density dependence, or the positive correlation between population density and individual fitness.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] It is sometimes referred to as "undercrowding" and it is analogous (or even considered synonymous by some) to "depensation" in the field of fishery sciences.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Listed below are a few significant subcategories of the Allee effect used in the ecology literature.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The *component Allee effect* is the positive relationship between any measurable component of individual fitness and population density.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The *demographic Allee effect* is the positive relationship between the overall individual fitness and population density.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The distinction between the two terms lies on the scale of the Allee effect: the presence of a demographic Allee effect suggests the presence of at least one component Allee effect, while the presence of a component Allee effect does not necessarily result in a demographic Allee effect.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] For example, cooperative hunting and the ability to more easily find mates, both influenced by population density, are component Allee effects, as they influence individual fitness of the population.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] At low population density, these component Allee effects would add up to produce an overall demographic Allee effect (increased fitness with higher population density).
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] When population density reaches a high number, negative density dependence often offsets the component Allee effects through resource competition, thus erasing the demographic Allee effect.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Allee effects might occur even at high population density for some species.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The *strong Allee effect* is a demographic Allee effect with a critical population size or density.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The *weak Allee effect* is a demographic Allee effect without a critical population size or density.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The distinction between the two terms is based on whether or not the population in question exhibits a critical population size or density.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] A population exhibiting a weak Allee effect will possess a reduced per capita growth rate (directly related to individual fitness of the population) at lower population density or size.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] However, even at this low population size or density, the population will always exhibit a positive per capita growth rate.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Meanwhile, a population exhibiting a strong Allee effect will have a critical population size or density under which the population growth rate becomes negative.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Therefore, when the population density or size hits a number below this threshold, the population will be destined for extinction without any further aid.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] A strong Allee effect is often easier to demonstrate empirically using time series data, as one can pinpoint the population size or density at which per capita growth rate becomes negative.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Due to its definition as the positive correlation between population density and average fitness, the mechanisms for which an Allee effect arises are therefore inherently tied to survival and reproduction.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] In general, these Allee effect mechanisms arise from cooperation or facilitation among individuals in the species.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Examples of such cooperative behaviors include better mate finding, environmental conditioning, and group defense against predators.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] As these mechanisms are more-easily observable in the field, they tend to be more commonly associated with the Allee effect concept.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Nevertheless, mechanisms of Allee effect that are less conspicuous such as inbreeding depression and sex ratio bias should be considered as well.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Although numerous ecological mechanisms for Allee effects exist, the list of most commonly cited facilitative behaviors that contribute to Allee effects in the literature include: mate limitation, cooperative defense, cooperative feeding, and environmental conditioning.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] While these behaviors are classified in separate categories, they can overlap and tend to be context dependent (will operate only under certain conditions – for example, cooperative defense will only be useful when there are predators or competitors present).
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Mate limitation refers to the difficulty of finding a compatible and receptive mate for sexual reproduction at lower population size or density.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] For example, wind-pollinated plants would have a lower fitness in sparse populations due to the lower likelihood of pollen successfully landing on a conspecific.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Another possible benefit of aggregation is to protect against predation by group anti-predator behavior.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Many species exhibit higher rates of predator vigilance behavior per individual at lower density.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This increased vigilance might result in less time and energy spent on foraging, thus reducing the fitness of an individual living in smaller groups.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The confusion effect that this herding behavior would have on predators will be more effective when more individuals are present.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Certain species also require group foraging in order to survive.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] , would not be able to locate and capture prey as efficiently in smaller groups.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Environmental conditioning generally refers to the mechanism in which individuals work together in order to improve their immediate or future environment for the benefit of the species.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This alteration could involve changes in both abiotic (temperature, turbulence, etc.) or biotic (toxins, hormones, etc.) environmental factors.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] present a potential case of such component Allee effects, where the density of spawning individuals can affect the survivability of the following generations.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Spawning salmon carry marine nutrients they acquired from the ocean as they migrate to freshwater streams to reproduce, which in turn fertilize the surrounding habitat when they die, thus creating a more suitable habitat for the juveniles that would hatch in the following months.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] While compelling, this case of environmental conditioning by salmon has not been rigorously supported by empirical evidence.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Classic economic theory predicts that human exploitation of a population is unlikely to result in species extinction because the escalating costs to find the last few individuals will exceed the fixed price one achieves by selling the individuals on the market.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] However, when rare species are more desirable than common species, prices for rare species can exceed high harvest costs.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This phenomenon can create an "anthropogenic" Allee effect where rare species go extinct but common species are sustainably harvested.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The anthropogenic Allee effect has become a standard approach for conceptualizing the threat of economic markets on endangered species.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] However, the original theory was posited using a one dimensional analysis of a two dimensional model.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] It turns out that a two dimensional analysis yields an Allee curve in human exploiter and biological population space and that this curve separating species destined to extinction vs persistence can be complicated.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Even very high population sizes can potentially pass through the originally proposed Allee thresholds on predestined paths to extinction.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Declines in population size can result in a loss of genetic diversity, and owing to genetic variation's role in the evolutionary potential of a species, this could in turn result in an observable Allee effect.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] As a species' population becomes smaller, its gene pool will be reduced in size as well.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] One possible outcome from this genetic bottleneck is a reduction in fitness of the species through the process of genetic drift, as well as inbreeding depression.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This overall fitness decrease of a species is caused by an accumulation of deleterious mutations throughout the population.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Genetic variation within a species could range from beneficial to detrimental.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Nevertheless, in a smaller sized gene pool, there is a higher chance of a stochastic event in which deleterious alleles become fixed (genetic drift).
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] While evolutionary theory states that expressed deleterious alleles should be purged through natural selection, purging would be most efficient only at eliminating alleles that are highly detrimental or harmful.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Mildly deleterious alleles such as those that act later in life would be less likely to be removed by natural selection, and conversely, newly acquired beneficial mutations are more likely to be lost by random chance in smaller genetic pools than larger ones.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Although the long-term population persistence of several species with low genetic variation has recently prompted debate on the generality of inbreeding depression, there are various empirical evidences for genetic Allee effects.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] One such case was observed in the endangered Florida panther (*Puma concolor coryi*).
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The Florida panther experienced a genetic bottleneck in the early 1990s where the population was reduced to ≈25 adult individuals.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This reduction in genetic diversity was correlated with defects that include lower sperm quality, abnormal testosterone levels, cowlicks, and kinked tails.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] In response, a genetic rescue plan was put in motion and several female pumas from Texas were introduced into the Florida population.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This action quickly led to the reduction in the prevalence of the defects previously associated with inbreeding depression.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Although the timescale for this inbreeding depression is larger than of those more immediate Allee effects, it has significant implications on the long-term persistence of a species.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Demographic stochasticity refers to variability in population growth arising from sampling random births and deaths in a population of finite size.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] In small populations, demographic stochasticity will decrease the population growth rate, causing an effect similar to the Allee effect, which will increase the risk of population extinction.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Whether or not demographic stochasticity can be considered a part of Allee effect is somewhat contentious however.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The most current definition of Allee effect considers the correlation between population density and mean individual fitness.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Therefore, random variation resulting from birth and death events would not be considered part of Allee effect as the increased risk of extinction is not a consequence of the changing fates of individuals within the population.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Meanwhile, when demographic stochasticity results in fluctuations of sex ratios, it arguably reduces the mean individual fitness as population declines.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] For example, a fluctuation in small population that causes a scarcity in one sex would in turn limit the access of mates for the opposite sex, decreasing the fitness of the individuals within the population.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This type of Allee effect will likely be more prevalent in monogamous species than polygynous species.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Demographic and mathematical studies demonstrate that the existence of an Allee effect can reduce the speed of range expansion of a population and can even prevent biological invasions.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Recent results based on spatio-temporal models show that the Allee effect can also promote genetic diversity in expanding populations.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] These results counteract commonly held notions that the Allee effect possesses net adverse consequences.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Reducing the growth rate of the individuals ahead of the colonization front simultaneously reduces the speed of colonization and enables a diversity of genes coming from the core of the population to remain on the front.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The Allee effect also affects the spatial distribution of diversity.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] A simple mathematical example of an Allee effect is given by the cubic growth model.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] where the population has a negative growth rate for $0<N<A$ , and a positive growth rate for $A<N<K$ (assuming $0<A<K$ ).
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] In contrast, when there is an Allee effect the per-capita growth rate increases with increasing *N* over some range of population sizes [0, *N*].
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] The Allee effect can be explicitly modeled using birth and death rates.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Here, $b_{0},b_{1},c,d$ are positive constants and $B(N)$ and $D(N)$ represent the per capita birth and death rates, respectively.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] This formulation is especially useful when demographic data is employed to identify parameters or when extending the model to stochastic differential equations.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Spatio-temporal models can take Allee effect into account as well.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] When a population is made up of small sub-populations additional factors to the Allee effect arise.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] In the case of a catastrophic event decreasing numbers at a sub-population, individuals from another sub-population site may be able to repopulate the area.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] If all sub-populations are subject to the same environmental variations (i.e. if a disaster affected one, it would affect them all) then fragmentation of the population is detrimental to the population and increases extinction risk for the total population.
[src:energy-quality/allee-effect] Clumping results due to individuals aggregating in response to: local habitat or landscape differences, daily and seasonal weather changes, reproductive processes, or as the result of social attractions.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Allometry is a well-known study, particularly in statistical shape analysis for its theoretical developments, as well as in biology for practical applications to the differential growth rates of the parts of a living organism's body.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] One application is in the study of various insect species (e.g., Hercules beetles), where a small change in overall body size can lead to an enormous and disproportionate increase in the dimensions of appendages such as legs, antennae, or horns.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] where a is the scaling exponent of the law.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Other methods include measurement-error models and a particular kind of principal component analysis.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Allometry often studies shape differences in terms of ratios of the objects' dimensions.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Two objects of different size, but common shape, have their dimensions in the same ratio.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Take, for example, a biological object that grows as it matures.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Its size changes with age, but the shapes are similar.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Studies of ontogenetic allometry often use lizards or snakes as model organisms both because they lack parental care after birth or hatching and because they exhibit a large range of body sizes between the juvenile and adult stage.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Lizards often exhibit allometric changes during their ontogeny.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In addition to studies that focus on growth, allometry also examines shape variation among individuals of a given age (and sex), which is referred to as static allometry.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Comparisons of species are used to examine interspecific or evolutionary allometry (see also Phylogenetic comparative methods).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Isometric scaling happens when proportional relationships are preserved as size changes during growth or over evolutionary time.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] An example is found in frogs—aside from a brief period during the few weeks after metamorphosis, frogs grow isometrically.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Therefore, a frog whose legs are as long as its body will retain that relationship throughout its life, even if the frog itself increases in size tremendously.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Isometric scaling is governed by the square–cube law.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] An organism which doubles in length isometrically will find that the surface area available to it will increase fourfold, while its volume and mass will increase by a factor of eight.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This can present problems for organisms.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In the case of above, the animal now has eight times the biologically active tissue to support, but the surface area of its respiratory organs has only increased fourfold, creating a mismatch between scaling and physical demands.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Similarly, the organism in the above example now has eight times the mass to support on its legs, but the strength of its bones and muscles is dependent upon their cross-sectional area, which has only increased fourfold.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Therefore, this hypothetical organism would experience twice the bone and muscle loads of its smaller version.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This mismatch can be avoided either by being "overbuilt" when small or by changing proportions during growth, called allometry.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Isometric scaling is often used as a null hypothesis in scaling studies, with 'deviations from isometry' considered evidence of physiological factors forcing allometric growth.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Allometric scaling is any change that deviates from isometry.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] A classic example discussed by Galileo in his *Dialogues Concerning Two New Sciences* is the skeleton of mammals.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The skeletal structure becomes much stronger and more robust relative to the size of the body as the body size increases.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Allometry is often expressed in terms of a scaling exponent based on body mass, or body length (snout–vent length, total length, etc.).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] A perfectly allometrically scaling organism would see all volume-based properties change proportionally to the body mass, all surface area-based properties change with mass to the power of 2/3, and all length-based properties change with mass to the power of 1/3.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] If, after statistical analyses, for example, a volume-based property was found to scale to mass to the 0.9th power, then this would be called "negative allometry", as the values are smaller than predicted by isometry.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Conversely, if a surface area-based property scales to mass to the 0.8th power, the values are higher than predicted by isometry and the organism is said to show "positive allometry".
[src:energy-quality/allometry] One example of positive allometry occurs among species of monitor lizards (family Varanidae), in which the limbs are relatively longer in larger-bodied species.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The same is true for some fish, e.g. the muskellunge, the weight of which grows with about the power of 3.325 of its length.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] A 30-inch (76 cm) muskellunge will weigh about 8 pounds (3.6 kg), while a 40-inch (100 cm) muskellunge will weigh about 18 pounds (8.2 kg), so 33% longer length will more than double the weight.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] To determine whether isometry or allometry is present, an expected relationship between variables needs to be determined to compare data to.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This is important in determining if the scaling relationship in a dataset deviates from an expected relationship (such as those that follow isometry).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Using tools such as dimensional analysis is very helpful in determining expected slope.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This 'expected' slope, as it is known, is essential for detecting allometry because scaling variables are comparisons to other things.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Saying that mass scales with a slope of 5 in relation to length doesn't have much meaning unless knowing the isometric slope is 3, meaning in this case, the mass is increasing extremely fast.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] For example, different sized frogs should be able to jump the same distance according to the geometric similarity model proposed by Hill 1950 and interpreted by Wilson 2000, but in actuality larger frogs do jump longer distances.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Data gathered in science do not fall neatly in a straight line, so data transformations are useful.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] It is also important to remember what is being compared in the data.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Comparing a characteristic such as head length to head width might yield different results from comparing head length to body length.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] That is, different characteristics may scale differently.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] A common way to analyze data such as those collected in scaling is to use log-transformation.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] There are two reasons why logarithmic transformation should be used to study allometry —a biological reason and a statistical reason.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Log-log transformation places numbers into a geometric domain so that proportional deviations are represented consistently, independent of the scale and units of measurement.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In biology, this is appropriate because many biological phenomena (e.g., growth, reproduction, metabolism, sensation) are fundamentally multiplicative.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Statistically, it is beneficial to transform both axes using logarithms and then perform a linear regression.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This will normalize the data set and make it easier to analyze trends using the slope of the line.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Before analyzing data, it is important to have a predicted slope of the line to compare the analysis to.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] After data are log-transformed and linearly regressed, comparisons can then use least squares regression with 95% confidence intervals or reduced major axis analysis.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Sometimes, the two analyses can yield different results, but often they do not.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] If the expected slope is outside the confidence intervals, allometry is present.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] If the mass in this imaginary animal scaled with a slope of 5, which was a statistically significant value, then mass would scale very fast in this animal versus the expected value.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] If the expected slope were 3 and in reality, in a certain organism mass scaled with 1 (assuming this slope is statistically significant), it would be negatively allometric.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] To find the expected slope for the relationship between mass and the characteristic length of an animal (see figure), the units of mass (M) from the y-axis are divided by the units of the x-axis, Length (L).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Another example: Force is dependent on the cross-sectional area of muscle (CSA), which is L2.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] If comparing force to a length, then the expected slope is 2.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Alternatively, this analysis may be accomplished with a power regression.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Plot the relationship between the data onto a graph.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Fit this to a power curve (depending on the stats program, this can be done multiple ways), and it will give an equation with the form: *y*=*Zx**n*, where *n* is the number.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] That "number" is the relationship between the data points.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The downside, to this form of analysis, is that it makes it a little more difficult to do statistical analyses.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Many physiological and biochemical processes (such as heart rate, respiration rate or the maximum reproduction rate) show scaling, mostly associated with the ratio between surface area and mass (or volume) of the animal.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The metabolic rate of an individual animal is also subject to scaling.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In plotting an animal's basal metabolic rate (BMR) against the animal's own body mass, a logarithmic straight line is obtained, indicating a power-law dependence.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Overall metabolic rate in animals is generally accepted to show negative allometry, scaling to mass to a power of ≈ 0.75, known as Kleiber's law, 1932.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This means that larger-bodied species (e.g., elephants) have lower mass-specific metabolic rates and lower heart rates, as compared with smaller-bodied species (e.g., mice).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The straight line generated from a double logarithmic scale of metabolic rate in relation to body mass is known as the "mouse-to-elephant curve".
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Max Kleiber contributed the following allometric equation for relating the BMR to the body mass of an animal.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] where M is body mass, and metabolic rate is measured in kcal per day.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Consequently, the body mass itself can explain the majority of the variation in the BMR.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] After the body mass effect, the taxonomy of the animal plays the next most significant role in the scaling of the BMR.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The further speculation that environmental conditions play a role in BMR can only be properly investigated once the role of taxonomy is established.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The challenge with this lies in the fact that a shared environment also indicates a common evolutionary history and thus a close taxonomic relationship.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] There are strides currently in research to overcome these hurdles; for example, an analysis in muroid rodents, the mouse, hamster, and vole type, took into account taxonomy.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Results revealed the hamster (warm dry habitat) had lowest BMR and the mouse (warm wet dense habitat) had the highest BMR.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Larger organs could explain the high BMR groups, along with their higher daily energy needs.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Analyses such as these demonstrate the physiological adaptations to environmental changes that animals undergo.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Energy metabolism is subjected to the scaling of an animal and can be overcome by an individual's body design.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The metabolic scope for an animal is the ratio of resting and maximum rate of metabolism for that particular species as determined by oxygen consumption.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Oxygen consumption VO2 and maximum oxygen consumption VO2 max.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Across a broad range of species, allometric relations are not necessarily linear on a log-log scale.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] For example, the maximal running speeds of mammals show a complicated relationship with body mass, and the fastest sprinters are of intermediate body size.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The muscle characteristics of animals are similar in a wide range of animal sizes, though muscle sizes and shapes can and often do vary depending on environmental constraints placed on them.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The muscle tissue itself maintains its contractile characteristics and does not vary depending on the size of the animal.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Physiological scaling in muscles affects the number of muscle fibers and their intrinsic speed to determine the maximum power and efficiency of movement in a given animal.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The speed of muscle recruitment varies roughly in inverse proportion to the cube root of the animal's weight (compare the intrinsic frequency of the sparrow's flight muscle to that of a stork).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] For inter-species allometric relations related to such ecological variables as maximal reproduction rate, attempts have been made to explain scaling within the context of dynamic energy budget theory and the metabolic theory of ecology.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] However, such ideas have been less successful.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Allometry has been used to study patterns in locomotive principles across a broad range of species.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Such research has been done in pursuit of a better understanding of animal locomotion, including the factors that different gaits seek to optimize.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Allometric trends observed in extant animals have even been combined with evolutionary algorithms to form realistic hypotheses concerning the locomotive patterns of extinct species.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] These studies have been made possible by the remarkable similarities among disparate species' locomotive kinematics and dynamics, "despite differences in morphology and size".
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Allometric study of locomotion involves the analysis of the relative sizes, masses, and limb structures of similarly shaped animals and how these features affect their movements at different speeds.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Patterns are identified based on dimensionless Froude numbers, which incorporate measures of animals' leg lengths, speed or stride frequency, and weight.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Alexander incorporates Froude-number analysis into his "dynamic similarity hypothesis" of gait patterns.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Dynamically similar gaits are those between which there are constant coefficients that can relate linear dimensions, time intervals, and forces.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In other words, given a mathematical description of gait A and these three coefficients, one could produce gait B, and vice versa.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The hypothesis itself is as follows: "animals of different sizes tend to move in dynamically similar fashion whenever the ratio of their speed allows it." While the dynamic similarity hypothesis may not be a truly unifying principle of animal gait patterns, it is a remarkably accurate heuristic.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] It has also been shown that living organisms of all shapes and sizes utilize spring mechanisms in their locomotive systems, probably in order to minimize the energy cost of locomotion.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The allometric study of these systems has fostered a better understanding of why spring mechanisms are so common, how limb compliance varies with body size and speed, and how these mechanisms affect general limb kinematics and dynamics.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The physiological effect of drugs and other substances in many cases scales allometrically.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] For example, plasma concentration of carotenoids scales to the three-quarter power of mass in nine predatory and scavenger raptor species.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] West, Brown, and Enquist in 1997 derived a hydrodynamic theory to explain the universal fact that metabolic rate scales as the 3⁄4 power with body weight.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] They also showed why lifespan scales as the +1⁄4 power and heart rate as the -1⁄4 power.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Blood flow (+3⁄4) and resistance (-3⁄4) scale in the same way, leading to blood pressure being constant across species.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Hu and Hayton in 2001 discussed whether the basal metabolic rate scale is a 2⁄3 or 3⁄4 power of body mass.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The exponent of 3⁄4 might be used for substances that are eliminated mainly by metabolism, or by metabolism and excretion combined, while 2⁄3 might apply for drugs that are eliminated mainly by renal excretion.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] An online allometric scaler of drug doses based on the above work is available.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) published guidance in 2005 giving a flow chart that presents the decisions and calculations used to generate the maximum recommended starting dose in drug clinical trials from animal data.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The mass and density of an organism have a large effect on the organism's locomotion through a fluid.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] For example, a tiny organism uses flagella and can effectively move through a fluid it is suspended in, while on the other end of the scale, a blue whale is much more massive and dense relative to the viscosity of the fluid compared to a bacterium in the same medium.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The way in which the fluid interacts with the external boundaries of the organism is important with locomotion through the fluid.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] For streamlined swimmers, the resistance or drag determines the performance of the organism.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Scaling also affects locomotion through a fluid because of the energy needed to propel an organism and keep up velocity through momentum.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The rate of oxygen consumption per gram body size decreases consistently with increasing body size.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In general, smaller, more streamlined organisms create laminar flow (*R* < 0.5x106), whereas larger, less streamlined organisms produce turbulent flow (*R* > 2.0×106).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Also, increase in velocity (V) increases turbulence, which can be proved using the Reynolds equation.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In nature however, organisms such as a 6-foot-6-inch (1.98 m) dolphin moving at 15 knots does not have the appropriate Reynolds numbers for laminar flow (*R* = 107), but exhibit it in nature.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Steven observed and documented dolphins moving at 15 knots alongside his ship leaving a single trail of light when phosphorescent activity in the sea was high.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Scaling also has an effect on the performance of organisms in fluid.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This is extremely important for marine mammals and other marine organisms that rely on atmospheric oxygen for respiration and survival.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This can affect how fast an organism can propel itself efficiently or how long and deep it can dive.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Heart mass and lung volume are important in determining how scaling can affect metabolic function and efficiency.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Aquatic mammals, like other mammals, have the same size heart proportional to their bodies.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In general, mammals have hearts about 0.6% of their total body mass: ${\text{Heart weight}}=0.006{M}^{1.0}$ , where *M* is the body mass of the individual.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Lung volume is also directly related to body mass in mammals (slope = 1.02).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The lung has a volume of 63 ml for every kg of body mass, with the tidal volume at rest being 1/10 the lung volume.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In addition, respiration costs with respect to oxygen consumption is scaled in the order of $M^{0.75}$ .
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This shows that mammals, regardless of size, have similarly scaled respiratory and cardiovascular systems and the same relative amount of blood: about 5.5% of body mass.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This means that for similarly designed marine mammals, a larger individual can travel more efficiently, as it takes the same effort to move one body length.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] For example, large whales can migrate far distance in the oceans and not stop for rest.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] It is metabolically less expensive to be larger in body size.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This goes for terrestrial and flying animals as well: smaller animals consume more oxygen per unit body mass than larger ones.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] The metabolic advantage in larger animals makes it possible for larger marine mammals to dive for longer durations of time than their smaller counterparts.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] That the heart rate is lower means that larger animals can carry more blood, which carries more oxygen.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In conjuncture with the fact that mammals reparation costs scales in the order of $M^{0.75}$ , this shows having a larger body mass can be advantageous.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] More simply, a larger whale can hold more oxygen and at the same time demand less metabolically than a smaller whale.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Traveling long distances and deep dives are a combination of good stamina and also moving an efficient speed and in an efficient way to create laminar flow, reducing drag and turbulence.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In sea water as the fluid, it traveling long distances in large mammals, such as whales, is facilitated by their neutral buoyancy and have their mass completely supported by the density of the sea water.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] On land, animals have to expend a portion of their energy during locomotion to fight the effects of gravity.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Flying organisms such as birds are also considered as moving through a fluid.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In scaling birds of similar shape, it has also been seen that larger individuals have less metabolic costs per kg, as expected.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Birds also have a variance in wing beat frequency.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Beyond the compensation of larger wings per unit body mass, larger birds also have slower wing beat frequencies, allowing them to fly at higher altitudes, longer distances, and faster absolute speeds than smaller birds.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Because of the dynamics of lift-based locomotion and the fluid dynamics, birds have a U-shaped curve for metabolic cost and velocity.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Because flight, in air as the fluid, is metabolically more costly at the lowest and the highest velocities.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] On the other end, small organisms such as insects can make gain advantage from the viscosity of the fluid (air) that they are moving in.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] A wing-beat timed perfectly can effectively uptake energy from the previous stroke (Dickinson 2000).
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This form of wake capture allows an organism to recycle energy from the fluid or vortices within that fluid created by the organism itself.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This same sort of wake capture occurs in aquatic organisms as well, and for organisms of all sizes.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This dynamic of fluid locomotion allows smaller organisms to gain advantage because the effect on them from the fluid is much greater because of their relatively smaller size.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Allometric engineering is a method for manipulating allometric relationships within or among groups.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Arguing that there are a number of analogous concepts and mechanisms between cities and biological entities, Bettencourt et al. showed a number of scaling relationships between observable properties of a city and the city size.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] GDP, "supercreative" employment, number of inventors, crime, spread of disease, and even pedestrian walking speeds scale with city population.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This phenomenon goes under the name of urban scaling.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Theoretical explanations for the presence of allometry in cities propose different mechanisms.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Bettencourt’s model suggests that superlinear scaling arises from the quadratic growth of social interactions with population size under budget constraints.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] A different mechanism was proposed by Gomez-Lievano et al. in which superlinear scaling is linked to the exponential growth in outputs resulting from the combination of diverse, complementary factors (or capabilities) found in cities, which scale logarithmically with city size.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Many factors go into the determination of body mass and size for a given animal.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] These factors often affect body size on an evolutionary scale, but conditions such as availability of food and habitat size can act much more quickly on a species.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Basic physiological design plays a role in the size of a given species.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] For example, animals with a closed circulatory system are larger than animals with open or no circulatory systems.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Mechanical design can also determine the maximum allowable size for a species.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] Animals with tubular endoskeletons tend to be larger than animals with exoskeletons or hydrostatic skeletons.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] is one of the largest determining factors in its size.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] On land, there is a positive correlation between body mass of the top species in the area and available land area.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] However, there are a much greater number of "small" species in any given area.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] This is most likely determined by ecological conditions, evolutionary factors, and the availability of food; a small population of large predators depend on a much greater population of small prey to survive.
[src:energy-quality/allometry] In an aquatic environment, the largest animals can grow to have a much greater body mass than land animals where gravitational weight constraints are a factor.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In ecology, the theory of **alternative stable states** (sometimes termed **alternate stable states** or **alternative stable equilibria**) predicts that ecosystems can exist under multiple "states" (sets of unique biotic and abiotic conditions).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] These alternative states are non-transitory and therefore considered stable over ecologically-relevant timescales.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Ecosystems may transition from one stable state to another, in what is known as a state shift (sometimes termed a phase shift or regime shift), when perturbed.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Due to ecological feedbacks, ecosystems display resistance to state shifts and therefore tend to remain in one state unless perturbations are large enough.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Multiple states may persist under equal environmental conditions, a phenomenon known as hysteresis.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] **Alternative stable state** theory suggests that discrete states are separated by ecological thresholds, in contrast to ecosystems which change smoothly and continuously along an environmental gradient.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Alternative stable state theory was first proposed by Richard Lewontin (1969), but other early key authors include Holling (1973), Sutherland (1974), May (1977), and Scheffer et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In the broadest sense, alternative stable state theory proposes that a change in ecosystem conditions can result in an abrupt shift in the state of the ecosystem, such as a change in population (Barange, M. et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Ecosystems can persist in states that are considered stable (i.e., can exist for relatively long periods of time).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Intermediate states are considered unstable and are, therefore, transitory.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Because ecosystems are resistant to state shifts, significant perturbations are usually required to overcome ecological thresholds and cause shifts from one stable state to another.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The resistance to state shifts is known as "resilience" (Holling 1973).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] State shifts are often illustrated heuristically by the ball-in-cup model (Holling, C.S. et al., 1995) Biodiversity in the functioning of ecosystems: an ecological synthesis.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In Biodiversity Loss, Ecological and Economical Issues (Perrings, C.A. et al., eds), pp.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] A ball, representing the ecosystem, exists on a surface where any point along the surface represents a possible state.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In the simplest model, the landscape consists of two valleys separated by a hill.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] When the ball is in a valley, or a "domain of attraction", it exists in a stable state and must be perturbed to move from this state.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In the absence of perturbations, the ball will always roll downhill and therefore will tend to stay in the valley (or stable state).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] State shifts can be viewed from two different viewpoints, the "community perspective" and the "ecosystem perspective".
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The ball can only move between stable states in two ways: (1) moving the ball or (2) altering the landscape.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The community perspective is analogous to moving the ball, while the ecosystem perspective is analogous to altering the landscape.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] These two viewpoints consider the same phenomenon with different mechanisms.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The community perspective considers ecosystem variables (which change relatively quickly and are subject to feedbacks from the system), whereas the ecosystem perspective considers ecosystem parameters (which change relatively slowly and operate independently of the system).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The community context considers a relatively constant environment in which multiple stable states are accessible to populations or communities.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] This definition is an extension of stability analysis of populations (e.g., Lewontin 1969; Sutherland 1973) and communities (e.g., Drake 1991; Law and Morton 1993).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The ecosystem context focuses on the effect of exogenic "drivers" on communities or ecosystems (e.g., May 1977; Scheffer et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Both definitions are explored within this article.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Ecosystems can shift from one state to another via a significant perturbation directly to state variables.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] State variables are quantities that change quickly (in ecologically-relevant time scales) in response to feedbacks from the system (i.e., they are dependent on system feedbacks), such as population densities.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] This perspective requires that different states can exist simultaneously under equal environmental conditions, since the ball moves only in response to a state variable change.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] For example, consider a very simple system with three microbial species.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] It may be possible for the system to exist under different community structure regimes depending on initial conditions (e.g., population densities or spatial arrangement of individuals) (Kerr et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Perhaps under certain initial densities or spatial configurations, one species dominates over all others, while under different initial conditions all species can mutually coexist.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Because the different species interact, changes in populations affect one another synergistically to determine community structure.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Under both states the environmental conditions are identical.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Because the states have resilience, following small perturbations (e.g., changes to population size) the community returns to the same configuration while large perturbations may induce a shift to another configuration.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The community perspective requires the existence of alternative stable states (i.e., more than one valley) before the perturbation, since the landscape is not changing.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Because communities have some level of resistance to change, they will stay in their domain of attraction (or stable state) until the perturbation is large enough to force the system into another state.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In the ball-and-cup model, this would be the energy required to push the ball up and over a hill, where it would fall downhill into a different valley.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] It is also possible to cause state shifts in another context, by indirectly affecting state variables.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] This is known as the ecosystem perspective.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] This perspective requires a change in environmental parameters that affect the behavior of state variables.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] For example, birth rate, death rate, migration, and density-dependent predation indirectly alter the ecosystem state by changing population density (a state variable).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Ecosystem parameters are quantities that are unresponsive (or respond very slowly) to feedbacks from the system (i.e., they are independent of system feedbacks).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The stable state landscape is changed by environmental drivers, which may result in a change in the quantity of stable states and the relationship between states.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] By the ecosystem perspective, the landscape of the ecological states is changed, which forces a change in the ecosystem state.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Changing the landscape can modify the number, location, and resilience of stable states, as well as the unstable intermediate states.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] By this view, the topography in the ball-and-cup model is not static, as it is in the community perspective.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] This is a fundamental difference between the two perspectives.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Although the mechanisms of community and ecosystem perspectives are different, the empirical evidence required for documentation of alternative stable states is the same.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In addition, state shifts are often a combination of internal processes and external forces (Scheffer et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] For example, consider a stream-fed lake in which the pristine state is dominated by benthic vegetation.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] When upstream construction releases soils into the stream, the system becomes turbid.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] As a result, benthic vegetation cannot receive light and decline, increasing nutrient availability and allowing phytoplankton to dominate.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In this state shift scenario the state variables changing are the populations of benthic vegetation and phytoplankton, and the ecosystem parameters are turbidity and nutrient levels.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] So, whether identifying mechanisms of variables or parameters is a matter of formulation (Beisner et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Hysteresis is an important concept in alternative stable state theory.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In this ecological context, hysteresis refers to the existence of different stable states under the same variables or parameters.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Hysteresis can be explained by "path-dependency", in which the equilibrium point for the trajectory of "A → B" is different from for "B → A".
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In other words, it matters which way the ball is moving across the landscape.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] 2001) argue that hysteresis is a prerequisite for the existence of alternative stable states.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] 2003) claim that this is not so; although shifts often involve hysteresis, a system can show alternative stable states yet have equal paths for "A → B" and "B → A".
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Hysteresis can occur via changes to variables or parameters.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] When variables are changed the ball is pushed from one domain of attraction to another, yet the same push from the other direction cannot return the ball to the original domain of attraction.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] When parameters are changed a modification to the landscape results in a state shift, but reversing the modification does not result in a reciprocal shift.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] A real-world example of hysteresis is helpful to illustrate the concept.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Coral reef systems can dramatically shift from pristine coral-dominated systems to degraded algae-dominated systems when populations grazing on algae decline.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The 1983 crash of sea urchin populations in Caribbean reef systems released algae from top-down (herbivory) control, allowing them to overgrow corals and resulting in a shift to a degraded state.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] When urchins rebounded, the high (pre-crash) coral cover levels did not return, indicating hysteresis (Mumby et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In some cases, state shifts under hysteresis may be irreversible.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] For example, tropical cloud forests require high moisture levels, provided by clouds that are intercepted by the canopy (via condensation).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] When deforested, moisture delivery ceases.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Therefore, reforestation is often unsuccessful because conditions are too dry to allow the trees to grow (Wilson & Agnew 1992).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Even in cases where there is no obvious barrier to recovery, alternative states can be remarkably persistent: an experimental grassland heavily fertilized for 10 years lost much of its biodiversity, and was still in this state 20 years later (Isbell et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] By their very nature, basins of attraction display resilience.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Ecosystems are resistant to state shifts – they will only undergo shifts under substantial perturbations – but some states are more resilient than others.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] In the ball-and-cup model, a valley with steep sides has greater resilience than a shallow valley, since it would take more force to push the ball up the hill and out of the valley.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Resilience can change in stable states when environmental parameters are shifted.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Often, humans influence stable states by reducing the resilience of basins of attraction.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] There are at least three ways in which anthropogenic forces reduce resilience (Folke et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] When the resilience is decreased, ecosystems can be pushed into alternative, and often less-desirable, stable states with only minor perturbations.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] When hysteresis effects are present, the return to a more-desirable state is sometimes impossible or impractical (given management constraints).
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Shifts to less-desirable states often entail a loss of ecosystem service and function, and have been documented in an array of terrestrial, marine, and freshwater environments (reviewed in Folke et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Most work on alternative stable states has been theoretical, using mathematical models and simulations to test ecological hypotheses.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Other work has been conducted using empirical evidence from surveying, historical records, or comparisons across spatial scales.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] There has been a lack of direct, manipulative experimental tests for alternative stable states.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] This is especially true for studies outside of controlled laboratory conditions, where state shifts have been documented for cultures of microorganisms.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Verifying the existence of alternative stable states carries profound implications for ecosystem management.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] If stable states exist, gradual changes in environmental factors may have little effect on a system until a threshold is reached, at which point a catastrophic state shift may occur.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Understanding the nature of these thresholds will help inform the design of monitoring programs, ecosystem restoration, and other management decisions.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Managers are particularly interested in the potential of hysteresis, since it may be difficult to recover from a state shift (Beisner et al.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] The mechanisms of feedback loops that maintain stable states are important to understand if we hope to effectively manage an ecosystem with alternative stable states.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Empirical evidence for the existence of alternative stable states is vital to advancing the idea beyond theory.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] (2005) reviewed the current ecological literature for alternative stable states and found 35 direct experiments, of which only 21 were deemed valid.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Of these, 62% (14) showed evidence for and 38% (8) showed no evidence for alternative stable states.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] (2005) analysis required evidence of hysteresis, which is not necessarily a prerequisite for alternative stable states.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] 2004) have had less-stringent requirements for the documentation of alternative stable states.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] (2003) suggest that commercially exploited fish populations can be forced between alternative stable states by fishing pressure due to Allee effect that work at very low population sizes.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Once a fish population falls below a certain threshold, it will inevitably go extinct when low population densities make replacement of adults impossible due to, for example, the inability to find mates or density-dependent mortality.
[src:energy-quality/alternative-stable-state] Since populations cannot return from extinction, this is an example of an irreversible state shift.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] There are several separate reasons why animals have evolved colours.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Camouflage enables an animal to remain hidden from view.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animals use colour to advertise services such as cleaning to animals of other species; to signal their sexual status to other members of the same species; and in mimicry, taking advantage of the warning coloration of another species.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some animals use flashes of colour to divert attacks by startling predators.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Zebras may possibly use motion dazzle, confusing a predator's attack by moving a bold pattern rapidly.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some animals are coloured for physical protection, with pigments in the skin to protect against sunburn, while some frogs can lighten or darken their skin for temperature regulation.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Finally, animals can be coloured incidentally.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For example, blood is red because the haem pigment needed to carry oxygen is red.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animals coloured in these ways can have striking natural patterns.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animals produce colour in both direct and indirect ways.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Direct production occurs through the presence of visible coloured cells known as pigment which are particles of coloured material such as freckles.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Indirect production occurs by virtue of cells known as chromatophores which are pigment-containing cells such as hair follicles.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The distribution of the pigment particles in the chromatophores can change under hormonal or neuronal control.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For fishes it has been demonstrated that chromatophores may respond directly to environmental stimuli like visible light, UV-radiation, temperature, pH, chemicals, etc. colour change helps individuals in becoming more or less visible and is important in agonistic displays and in camouflage.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some animals, including many butterflies and birds, have microscopic structures in scales, bristles or feathers which give them brilliant iridescent colours.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Other animals including squid and some deep-sea fish can produce light, sometimes of different colours.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animals often use two or more of these mechanisms together to produce the colours and effects they need.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animal coloration has been a topic of interest and research in biology for centuries.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In the classical era, Aristotle recorded that the octopus was able to change its coloration to match its background, and when it was alarmed.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] According to Charles Darwin's 1859 theory of natural selection, features such as coloration evolved by providing individual animals with a reproductive advantage.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For example, individuals with slightly better camouflage than others of the same species would, on average, leave more offspring.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Henry Walter Bates's 1863 book *The Naturalist on the River Amazons* describes his extensive studies of the insects in the Amazon basin, and especially the butterflies.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] He discovered that apparently similar butterflies often belonged to different families, with a harmless species mimicking a poisonous or bitter-tasting species to reduce its chance of being attacked by a predator, in the process now called after him, Batesian mimicry.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Edward Bagnall Poulton's strongly Darwinian 1890 book *The Colours of Animals, their meaning and use, especially considered in the case of insects* argued the case for three aspects of animal coloration that are broadly accepted today but were controversial or wholly new at the time.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] It strongly supported Darwin's theory of sexual selection, arguing that the obvious differences between male and female birds such as the argus pheasant were selected by the females, pointing out that bright male plumage was found only in species "which court by day".
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The book introduced the concept of frequency-dependent selection, as when edible mimics are less frequent than the distasteful models whose colours and patterns they copy.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In the book, Poulton also coined the term aposematism for warning coloration, which he identified in widely differing animal groups including mammals (such as the skunk), bees and wasps, beetles, and butterflies.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Frank Evers Beddard's 1892 book, *Animal Coloration*, acknowledged that natural selection existed but examined its application to camouflage, mimicry and sexual selection very critically.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The book was in turn roundly criticised by Poulton.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Abbott Handerson Thayer's 1909 book *Concealing-Coloration in the Animal Kingdom*, completed by his son Gerald H.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Thayer, argued correctly for the widespread use of crypsis among animals, and in particular described and explained countershading for the first time.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] However, the Thayers spoilt their case by arguing that camouflage was the sole purpose of animal coloration, which led them to claim that even the brilliant pink plumage of the flamingo or the roseate spoonbill was cryptic—against the momentarily pink sky at dawn or dusk.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Hugh Bamford Cott's 500-page book *Adaptive Coloration in Animals*, published in wartime 1940, systematically described the principles of camouflage and mimicry.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The book contains hundreds of examples, over a hundred photographs and Cott's own accurate and artistic drawings, and 27 pages of references.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Cott focussed especially on "maximum disruptive contrast", the kind of patterning used in military camouflage such as disruptive pattern material.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animal coloration provided important early evidence for evolution by natural selection, at a time when little direct evidence was available.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] One of the pioneers of research into animal coloration, Edward Bagnall Poulton classified the forms of protective coloration, in a way which is still helpful.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] He described: protective resemblance; aggressive resemblance; adventitious protection; and variable protective resemblance.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Protective resemblance is used by prey to avoid predation.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] It includes special protective resemblance, now called mimesis, where the whole animal looks like some other object, for example when a caterpillar resembles a twig or a bird dropping.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In general protective resemblance, now called crypsis, the animal's texture blends with the background, for example when a moth's colour and pattern blend in with tree bark.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Aggressive resemblance is used by predators or parasites.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In special aggressive resemblance, the animal looks like something else, luring the prey or host to approach, for example when a flower mantis resembles a particular kind of flower, such as an orchid.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In general aggressive resemblance, the predator or parasite blends in with the background, for example when a leopard is hard to see in long grass.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For adventitious protection, an animal uses materials such as twigs, sand, or pieces of shell to conceal its outline, for example when a caddis fly larva builds a decorated case, or when a decorator crab decorates its back with seaweed, sponges and stones.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In variable protective resemblance, an animal such as a chameleon, flatfish, squid or octopus changes its skin pattern and colour using special chromatophore cells to resemble whatever background it is currently resting on (as well as for signalling).
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Countershading was first described by the American artist Abbott Handerson Thayer, a pioneer in the theory of animal coloration.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Thayer's observation "Animals are painted by Nature, darkest on those parts which tend to be most lighted by the sky's light, and *vice versa*" is called *Thayer's Law*.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Colour is widely used for signalling in animals as diverse as birds and shrimps.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Advertising coloration can signal the services an animal offers to other animals.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] These may be of the same species, as in sexual selection, or of different species, as in cleaning symbiosis.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Signals, which often combine colour and movement, may be understood by many different species; for example, the cleaning stations of the banded coral shrimp *Stenopus hispidus* are visited by different species of fish, and even by reptiles such as hawksbill sea turtles.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Darwin observed that the males of some species, such as birds-of-paradise, were very different from the females.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Darwin explained such male-female differences in his theory of sexual selection in his book *The Descent of Man*.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Once the females begin to select males according to any particular characteristic, such as a long tail or a coloured crest, that characteristic is emphasised more and more in the males.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Eventually all the males will have the characteristics that the females are sexually selecting for, as only those males can reproduce.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] This mechanism is powerful enough to create features that are strongly disadvantageous to the males in other ways.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For example, some male birds-of-paradise have wing or tail streamers that are so long that they impede flight, while their brilliant colours may make the males more vulnerable to predators.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In the extreme, sexual selection may drive species to extinction, as has been argued for the enormous horns of the male Irish elk, which may have made it difficult for mature males to move and feed.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Different forms of sexual selection are possible, including rivalry among males, and selection of females by males.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Warning coloration (aposematism) is effectively the "opposite" of camouflage, and a special case of advertising.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Its function is to make the animal, for example a wasp or a coral snake, highly conspicuous to potential predators, so that it is noticed, remembered, and then avoided.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] As Peter Forbes observes, "Human warning signs employ the same colours – red, yellow, black, and white – that nature uses to advertise dangerous creatures." Warning colours work by being associated by potential predators with something that makes the warning coloured animal unpleasant or dangerous.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Warning coloration can succeed either through inborn behaviour (instinct) on the part of potential predators, or through a learned avoidance.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Either can lead to various forms of mimicry.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Experiments show that avoidance is learned in birds, mammals, lizards, and amphibians, but that some birds such as great tits have inborn avoidance of certain colours and patterns such as black and yellow stripes.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Mimicry means that one species of animal resembles another species closely enough to deceive predators.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] To evolve, the mimicked species must have warning coloration, because appearing to be bitter-tasting or dangerous gives natural selection something to work on.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Once a species has a slight, chance, resemblance to a warning coloured species, natural selection can drive its colours and patterns towards more perfect mimicry.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some animals such as many moths, mantises and grasshoppers, have a repertoire of threatening or startling behaviour, such as suddenly displaying conspicuous eyespots or patches of bright and contrasting colours, so as to scare off or momentarily distract a predator.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] This gives the prey animal an opportunity to escape.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The behaviour is deimatic (startling) rather than aposematic as these insects are palatable to predators, so the warning colours are a bluff, not an honest signal.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some prey animals such as zebra are marked with high-contrast patterns which possibly help to confuse their predators, such as lions, during a chase.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The bold stripes of a herd of running zebra have been claimed make it difficult for predators to estimate the prey's speed and direction accurately, or to identify individual animals, giving the prey an improved chance of escape.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Since dazzle patterns (such as the zebra's stripes) make animals harder to catch when moving, but easier to detect when stationary, there is an evolutionary trade-off between dazzle and camouflage.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] There is evidence that the zebra's stripes could provide some protection from flies and biting insects.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Many animals have dark pigments such as melanin in their skin, eyes and fur to protect themselves against sunburn (damage to living tissues caused by ultraviolet light).
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Another example of photoprotective pigments are the GFP-like proteins in some corals.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In some jellyfish, rhizostomins have also been hypothesised to protect against ultraviolet damage.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some frogs such as *Bokermannohyla alvarengai*, which basks in sunlight, lighten their skin colour when hot (and darkens when cold), making their skin reflect more heat and so avoid overheating.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some animals are coloured purely incidentally because their blood contains pigments.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For example, amphibians like the olm that live in caves may be largely colourless as colour has no function in that environment, but they show some red because of the haem pigment in their red blood cells, needed to carry oxygen.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] They also have a little orange coloured riboflavin in their skin.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Human albinos and people with fair skin have a similar colour for the same reason.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animal coloration may be the result of any combination of pigments, chromatophores, structural coloration and bioluminescence.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Pigments are coloured chemicals (such as melanin) in animal tissues.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For example, the Arctic fox has a white coat in winter (containing little pigment), and a brown coat in summer (containing more pigment), an example of seasonal camouflage (a polyphenism).
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Many animals, including mammals, birds, and amphibians, are unable to synthesise most of the pigments that colour their fur or feathers, other than the brown or black melanins that give many mammals their earth tones.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For example, the bright yellow of an American goldfinch, the startling orange of a juvenile red-spotted newt, the deep red of a cardinal and the pink of a flamingo are all produced by carotenoid pigments synthesised by plants.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] In the case of the flamingo, the bird eats pink shrimps, which are themselves unable to synthesise carotenoids.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The shrimps derive their body colour from microscopic red algae, which like most plants are able to create their own pigments, including both carotenoids and (green) chlorophyll.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animals that eat green plants do not become green, however, as chlorophyll does not survive digestion.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Chromatophores are special pigment-containing cells that may change their size, but more often retain their original size but allow the pigment within them to become redistributed, thus varying the colour and pattern of the animal.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Chromatophores may respond to hormonal and/or neurobal control mechanisms, but direst responses to stimulation by visible light, UV-radiation, temperature, pH-changes, chemicals, etc. have also been documented.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The voluntary control of chromatophores is known as metachrosis.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Cephalopod molluscs like squid can voluntarily change their coloration by contracting or relaxationg small muscles around their chromatophores.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The energy cost of the complete activation of the chromatophore system is very high, equalling nearly as much as all the energy used by an octopus at rest.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Amphibians such as frogs have three kinds of star-shaped chromatophore cells in separate layers of their skin.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] The top layer contains 'xanthophores' with orange, red, or yellow pigments; the middle layer contains 'iridophores' with a silvery light-reflecting pigment; while the bottom layer contains 'melanophores' with dark melanin.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] While many animals are unable to synthesise carotenoid pigments to create red and yellow surfaces, the green and blue colours of bird feathers and insect carapaces are usually not produced by pigments at all, but by structural coloration.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Structural coloration means the production of colour by microscopically-structured surfaces fine enough to interfere with visible light, sometimes in combination with pigments: for example, peacock tail feathers are pigmented brown, but their structure makes them appear blue, turquoise and green.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Structural coloration can produce the most brilliant colours, often iridescent.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] For example, the blue/green gloss on the plumage of birds such as ducks, and the purple/blue/green/red colours of many beetles and butterflies are created by structural coloration.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Animals use several methods to produce structural colour, as described in the table.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Bioluminescence is the production of light, such as by the photophores of marine animals, and the tails of glow-worms and fireflies.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Bioluminescence, like other forms of metabolism, releases energy derived from the chemical energy of food.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] A pigment, luciferin is catalysed by the enzyme luciferase to react with oxygen, releasing light.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Comb jellies such as *Euplokamis* are bioluminescent, creating blue and green light, especially when stressed; when disturbed, they secrete an ink which luminesces in the same colours.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Since comb jellies are not very sensitive to light, their bioluminescence is unlikely to be used to signal to other members of the same species (e.g. to attract mates or repel rivals); more likely, the light helps to distract predators or parasites.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some species of squid have light-producing organs (photophores) scattered all over their undersides that create a sparkling glow.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] This provides counter-illumination camouflage, preventing the animal from appearing as a dark shape when seen from below.
[src:energy-quality/animal-coloration] Some anglerfish of the deep sea, where it is too dark to hunt by sight, contain symbiotic bacteria in the 'bait' on their 'fishing rods'.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The consideration of energy quality was a fundamental driver of industrialization from the 18th through 20th centuries.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Consider for example the industrialization of New England in the 18th century.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] This refers to the construction of textile mills containing power looms for weaving cloth.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The simplest, most economical and straightforward source of energy was provided by water wheels, extracting energy from a millpond behind a dam on a local creek.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] If another nearby landowner also decided to build a mill on the same creek, the construction of their dam would lower the overall hydraulic head to power the existing waterwheel, thus hurting power generation and efficiency.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] This eventually became an issue endemic to the entire region, reducing the overall profitability of older mills as newer ones were built.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The search for higher quality energy was a major impetus throughout the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] For example, burning coal to make steam to generate mechanical energy would not have been imaginable in the 18th century; by the end of the 19th century, the use of water wheels was long outmoded.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Similarly, the quality of energy from electricity offers immense advantages over steam, but did not become economic or practical until the 20th century.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The above example focused on the economic impacts of the exploitation of energy.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] A similar scenario plays out in nature and biology, where living organisms can extract energy of varying quality from nature, ultimately driven by solar energy as the primary driver of thermodynamic disequilibrium on Earth.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The ecological balance of ecosystems is predicated on the energy flows through the system.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Water wheels are also driven by rainwater, via the solar evaporation-condensation water cycle; thus ultimately, industrial cloth-making was driven by the day-night cycle of solar irradiation.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] This is a holistic view of energy sources as a system-in-the-large.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Thus, discussions of energy quality can sometimes be found in the Humanities, such as dialectics, Marxism and postmodernism.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Thus, the broad-stroke, global system-in-the-large discussions were taken up by those best trained for the nebulous, non-specific reasoning that such complex systems require.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The resulting mismatch of vocabulary and outlook across disciplines can lead to considerable contention.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] According to Ohta, the ranking and scientific analysis of energy quality was first proposed in 1851 by William Thomson under the concept of "availability".
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] This concept was continued in Germany by Z.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Rant, who developed it under the title, "die Exergie" (the exergy).
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] It was later continued and standardised in Japan.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Exergy analysis now forms a common part of many industrial and ecological energy analyses.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] 132) state that energy forms of different qualities are now commonly dealt with in steam power engineering industry.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Here the "quality index" is the relation of exergy to the energy content (Ibid.).
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] However energy engineers were aware that the notion of heat quality involved the notion of value – for example A.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Thumann wrote, "The essential quality of heat is not the amount but rather its 'value'" – which brings into play the question of teleology and wider, or ecological-scale goal functions.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Bendoricchio say that energy is used as a goal function in ecological models, and expresses energy "with a built-in measure of quality like energy" (2001, p.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] There appear to be two main kinds of methodology used for the calculation of energy quality.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] These can be classed as either receiver or donor methods.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] One of the main differences that distinguishes these classes is the assumption of whether energy quality can be upgraded in an energy transformation process.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Ohta suggested that the concept of energy quality may be more intuitive if one considers examples where the form of energy remains constant but the amount of energy flowing, or transferred is varied.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] For instance if we consider only the inertial form of energy, then the energy quality of a moving body is higher when it moves with a greater velocity.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] If we consider only the heat form of energy, then a higher temperature has higher quality.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] And if we consider only the light form of energy then light with higher frequency has greater quality.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] All these differences in energy quality are therefore easily measured with the appropriate scientific instrument.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The situation becomes more complex when the form of energy does not remain constant.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] In this context Ohta formulated the question of energy quality in terms of the conversion of energy of one form into another, that is the **transformation** of energy.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Here, energy quality is defined by the **relative ease** with which the energy transforms, from form to form.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The notion of energy quality was also recognised in the economic sciences.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] In the context of biophysical economics energy quality was measured by the amount of economic output generated per unit of energy input.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The estimation of energy quality in an economic context is also associated with embodied energy methodologies.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Another example of the economic relevance of the energy quality concept is given by Brian Fleay.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Fleay says that the "Energy Profit Ratio (EPR) is one measure of energy quality and a pivotal index for assessing the economic performance of fuels.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Both the direct and indirect energy inputs embodied in goods and services must be included in the denominator." (2006; p.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] 10) Fley calculates the EPR as the energy output/energy input.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Ohta sought to order energy form conversions according to their quality and introduced a hierarchical scale for ranking energy quality based on the relative ease of energy conversion (see table to right after Ohta, p.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] It is evident that Ohta did not analyse all forms of energy.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] For example, water is left out of his evaluation.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] The ranking of energy quality is not determined solely with reference to the efficiency of the energy conversion.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] This is to say that the evaluation of "relative ease" of an energy conversion is only partly dependent on transformation efficiency.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Ohta therefore also included, 'abundance in nature' as another criterion for the determination energy quality rank.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] For example, Ohta said that, "the only electrical energy which exists in natural circumstances is lightning, while many mechanical energies exist." (See also table 1. in Wall's article for another example ranking of energy quality).
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Odum also sought to order energy form conversions according to their quality, however his hierarchical scale for ranking was based on extending ecological system food chain concepts to thermodynamics rather than simply relative ease of transformation.
[src:energy-quality/energy-quality] Odum, energy quality rank is based on the amount of energy of one form required to generate a unit of another energy form.
